881.name: find_cross_t
881.docs:
Find out the t value for the point where the curve is intersected with the base line.
The base line is the line from P0 to P3.
If the curve only has two intersection points with the base line, they should be 0.0 and 1.0.
In this case, the "fill" will be simple since the curve is a convex line.
If the curve has more than two intersection points with the base line, the "fill" will be a problem.
We need to find out where is the 3rd t value (0<t<1)
And the original cubic curve will be split into two curves (0.0..t and t..1.0).
B(t) = (1-t)^3*P0 + 3*t*(1-t)^2*P1 + 3*t^2*(1-t)*P2 + t^3*P3
or B(t) = (P3 - 3*P2 + 3*P1 - P0)*t^3 + (3*P2 - 6*P1 + 3*P0)*t^2 + (3*P1 - 3*P0)*t + P0
this B(t) should be on the line between P0 and P3. Therefore:
(B.x - P0.x)/(P3.x - P0.x) = (B.y - P0.y)/(P3.y - P0.y), or:
B.x * (P3.y - P0.y) - B.y * (P3.x - P0.x) + P0.x * (P0.y - P3.y) + P0.y * (P3.x - P0.x) = 0
B.x = (P3.x - 3 * P2.x + 3 * P1.x - P0.x) * t^3 + (3 * P2.x - 6 * P1.x + 3 * P0.x) * t^2 + (3 * P1.x - 3 * P0.x) * t + P0.x
B.y = (P3.y - 3 * P2.y + 3 * P1.y - P0.y) * t^3 + (3 * P2.y - 6 * P1.y + 3 * P0.y) * t^2 + (3 * P1.y - 3 * P0.y) * t + P0.y
Combine the above three equations and iliminate B.x and B.y, we get:
```text
t^3 * ( (P3.x - 3*P2.x + 3*P1.x - P0.x) * (P3.y - P0.y) - (P3.y - 3*P2.y + 3*P1.y - P0.y) * (P3.x - P0.x))
+ t^2 * ( (3 * P2.x - 6 * P1.x + 3 * P0.x) * (P3.y - P0.y) - (3 * P2.y - 6 * P1.y + 3 * P0.y) * (P3.x - P0.x))
+ t^1 * ( (3 * P1.x - 3 * P0.x) * (P3.y - P0.y) - (3 * P1.y - 3 * P0.y) * (P3.x - P0.x))
+ (P0.x * (P3.y - P0.y) - P0.y * (P3.x - P0.x)) + P0.x * (P0.y - P3.y) + P0.y * (P3.x - P0.x)
= 0
```
or `a * t^3 + b * t^2 + c * t + d = 0`

let x = t - b / (3 * a), then we have:
```text
x^3 + p * x + q = 0, where:
p = (3.0 * a * c - b^2) / (3.0 * a^2)
q = (2.0 * b^3 - 9.0 * a * b * c + 27.0 * a^2 * d) / (27.0 * a^3)
```

when p > 0, there will be one real root, two complex roots
when p = 0, there will be two real roots, when p=q=0, there will be three real roots but all 0.
when p < 0, there will be three unique real roots. this is what we need. (x1, x2, x3)
 t = x + b / (3 * a), then we have: t1, t2, t3.
the one between 0.0 and 1.0 is what we need.
<`https://baike.baidu.com/item/%E4%B8%80%E5%85%83%E4%B8%89%E6%AC%A1%E6%96%B9%E7%A8%8B/8388473 /`>

1735.name: column
1735.docs:
Character based (NOT bytes).
It is fine if this points to something beyond the end of the current row.
When moving up/down it may again be within the next row.

1181.name: Noop
1181.docs: Paint nothing. This can be useful as a placeholder.

1281.name: opacity_factor
1281.docs:
If set, the text will be rendered with the given opacity in gamma space
Affects everything: backgrounds, glyphs, strikethrough, underline, etc.

1608.name: debug_ignore_clip_rects
1608.docs: If true, no clipping will be done.

827.name: margin
827.docs: How much larger than the parent rect are we in each direction?

927.name: flatten
927.docs:
find a set of points that approximate the quadratic Bézier curve.
the number of points is determined by the tolerance.
the points may not be evenly distributed in the range [0.0,1.0] (t value)

2135.name: TextWrapping
2135.docs: Controls the text wrapping and elision of a [`LayoutJob`].

700.name: translate
700.docs: Translate location by this much, in-place

346.name: region_by_pixels
346.docs: Clone a sub-region as a new image.

1227.name: Galley
1227.docs:
Text that has been laid out, ready for painting.

You can create a [`Galley`] using [`crate::Fonts::layout_job`];

Needs to be recreated if the underlying font atlas texture changes, which
happens under the following conditions:
- `pixels_per_point` or `max_texture_size` change. These parameters are set
  in [`crate::text::Fonts::begin_pass`]. When using `egui` they are set
  from `egui::InputState` and can change at any time.
- The atlas has become full. This can happen any time a new glyph is added
  to the atlas, which in turn can happen any time new text is laid out.

The name comes from typography, where a "galley" is a metal tray
containing a column of set type, usually the size of a page of text.

1554.name: fill_with_uv
1554.docs:
Like [`Self::fill`] but with texturing.

The `uv_from_pos` is called for each vertex position.

1881.name: index
1881.docs:
Which font face in the file to use.
When in doubt, use `0`.

1654.name: new
1654.docs:
Create a new [`Tessellator`].

* `pixels_per_point`: number of physical pixels to each logical point
* `options`: tessellation quality
* `shapes`: what to tessellate
* `font_tex_size`: size of the font texture. Required to normalize glyph uv rectangles when tessellating text.
* `prepared_discs`: What [`crate::TextureAtlas::prepared_discs`] returns. Can safely be set to an empty vec.

2735.name: NEAREST_MIRRORED_REPEAT
2735.docs: Nearest magnification and minification, but with the texture mirrored and repeated.

292.name: ImageData
292.docs:
An image stored in RAM.

To load an image file, see [`ColorImage::from_rgba_unmultiplied`].

This is currently an enum with only one variant, but more image types may be added in the future.

See also: [`ColorImage`].

1500.name: outside
1500.docs: Set the stroke to be painted entirely outside of the shape

1046.name: PaintCallback
1046.docs:
If you want to paint some 3D shapes inside an egui region, you can use this.

This is advanced usage, and is backend specific.

819.name: mutex
819.docs: Helper module that adds extra checks when the `deadlock_detection` feature is turned on.

1146.name: with_texture
1146.docs: Set the texture to use when painting this rectangle, if any.

692.name: append_ref
692.docs:
Append all the indices and vertices of `other` to `self` without
taking ownership.

Panics when `other` mesh has a different texture.

2454.name: visuals
2454.docs: The mesh, ready to be rendered.

2881.name: top_px
2881.docs: Physical pixel offset for top side of the viewport.

1092.name: closed
1092.docs:
If true, connect the first and last of the points together.
This is required if `fill != TRANSPARENT`.

2300.name: break_anywhere
2300.docs:
If `true`: Allow breaking between any characters.
If `false` (default): prefer breaking between words, etc.

NOTE: Due to limitations in the current implementation,
when truncating text using [`Self::max_rows`] the text may be truncated
in the middle of a word even if [`Self::break_anywhere`] is `false`.
Therefore it is recommended to set [`Self::break_anywhere`] to `true`
whenever [`Self::max_rows`] is set to `1`.

1192.name: Path
1192.docs:
A series of lines between points.
The path can have a stroke and/or fill (if closed).

2073.name: layout
2073.docs:
Will wrap text at the given width and line break at `\n`.

The implementation uses memoization so repeated calls are cheap.

2727.name: wrap_mode
2727.docs: How to wrap the texture when the texture coordinates are outside the [0, 1] range.

738.name: Shape
738.docs:
A paint primitive such as a circle or a piece of text.
Coordinates are all screen space points (not physical pixels).

You should generally recreate your [`Shape`]s each frame,
but storing them should also be fine with one exception:
[`Shape::Text`] depends on the current `pixels_per_point` (dpi scale)
and so must be recreated every time `pixels_per_point` changes.

1392.name: ClippedShape
1392.docs:
A [`Shape`] within a clip rectangle.

Everything is using logical points.

2146.name: TextFormat
2146.docs: Formatting option for a section of text.

1919.name: scale
1919.docs:
Scale the font's glyphs by this much.
this is only a visual effect and does not affect the text layout.

Default: `1.0` (no scaling).

1692.name: CCursor
1692.docs:
Character cursor.

The default cursor is zero.

1138.name: blur_width
1138.docs:
If larger than zero, the edges of the rectangle
(for both fill and stroke) will be blurred.

This can be used to produce shadows and glow effects.

The blur is currently implemented using a simple linear blur in sRGBA gamma space.

2346.name: pixels_per_point
2346.docs:
The number of physical pixels for each logical point.
Since this affects the layout, we keep track of it
so that we can warn if this has changed once we get to
tessellation.

2673.name: meta
2673.docs: Get meta-data about a specific texture.

1238.name: scale
1238.docs:
Scale the shape by `factor`, in-place.

A wrapper around [`Self::transform`].

130.name: CornerRadiusF32
130.docs:
How rounded the corners of things should be, in `f32`.

This is used for calculations, but storage is usually done with the more compact [`CornerRadius`].

2219.name: line_height
2219.docs:
Explicit line height of the text in points.

This is the distance between the bottom row of two subsequent lines of text.

If `None` (the default), the line height is determined by the font.

For even text it is recommended you round this to an even number of _pixels_.

1665.name: tessellate_rect
1665.docs:
Tessellate a single [`Rect`] into a [`Mesh`].

* `rect`: the rectangle to tessellate.
* `out`: triangles are appended to this.

884.name: flatten_closed
884.docs:
find a set of points that approximate the cubic Bézier curve.
the number of points is determined by the tolerance.
the points may not be evenly distributed in the range [0.0,1.0] (t value)
this api will check whether the curve will cross the base line or not when closed = true.
The result will be a vec of vec of Pos2. it will store two closed aren in different vec.
The epsilon is used to compare a float value.

1611.name: parallel_tessellation
1611.docs: If `rayon` feature is activated, should we parallelize tessellation?

2492.name: mesh_bounds
2492.docs:
Bounds of the mesh, and can be used for culling.
Does NOT include leading or trailing whitespace glyphs!!

2265.name: Truncate
2265.docs:
The text should be elided using "…" when reaching the `Ui` boundary.

Note that using [`TextWrapping`] and [`LayoutJob`] offers more control over the elision.

2138.name: halign
2138.docs: How to horizontally align the text (`Align::LEFT`, `Align::Center`, `Align::RIGHT`).

703.name: rotate
703.docs:
Rotate by some angle about an origin, in-place.

Origin is a position in screen space.

2338.name: rows
2338.docs:
Rows of text, from top to bottom, and their offsets.

The number of characters in all rows sum up to `job.text.chars().count()`
unless [`Self::elided`] is `true`.

Note that a paragraph (a piece of text separated with `\n`)
can be split up into multiple rows.

2665.name: take_delta
2665.docs:
Take and reset changes since last frame.

These should be applied to the painting subsystem each frame.

1884.name: FontData
1884.docs: A `.ttf` or `.otf` file and a font face index.

1657.name: tessellate_clipped_shape
1657.docs: Tessellate a clipped shape into a list of primitives.

222.name: ne
222.docs: Radius of the rounding of the North-East (right top) corner.

876.name: visual_bounding_rect
876.docs: The visual bounding rectangle (includes stroke width)

2411.name: pos
2411.docs:
The position of this [`Row`] relative to the galley.

This is rounded to the closest _pixel_ in order to produce crisp, pixel-perfect text.

1830.name: Proportional
1830.docs:
A font where some characters are wider than other (e.g. 'w' is wider than 'i').

Proportional fonts are easier to read and should be the preferred choice in most situations.

1276.name: pos
1276.docs:
Where the origin of [`Self::galley`] is.

Usually the top left corner of the first character.

1603.name: prerasterized_discs
1603.docs:
If `true`, small filled circled will be optimized by using pre-rasterized circled
from the font atlas.

1049.name: viewport_in_pixels
1049.docs: The viewport rectangle. This is what you would use in e.g. `glViewport`.

822.name: spread
822.docs: Expand the shadow in all directions by this much.

2584.name: uv
2584.docs:
Where in the texture atlas the disc is.
Normalized in 0-1 range.

1149.name: fill_texture_id
1149.docs:
The texture to use when painting this rectangle, if any.

If no texture is set, this will return [`TextureId::default`].

2357.name: begin
2357.docs:
Cursor to the first character.

This is the same as [`CCursor::default`].

922.name: transform
922.docs: Transform the curve with the given transform.

2130.name: text
2130.docs: Everything related to text, fonts, text layout, cursors etc.

695.name: reserve_triangles
695.docs:
Make room for this many additional triangles (will reserve 3x as many indices).
See also `reserve_vertices`.

2457.name: text
2457.docs: The text on this row, excluding the implicit `\n` if any.

568.name: is_same
568.docs: Are the margin on every side the same?

341.name: with_source_size
341.docs: Set the source size of e.g. the original SVG image.

1095.name: line_segment
1095.docs:
A line between two points.
More efficient than calling [`Self::line`].

2303.name: wrap_at_width
2303.docs: A row can be at most `max_width` wide but can wrap in any number of lines.

1422.name: is_empty
1422.docs: True if width is zero or color is transparent

868.name: PathStroke
868.docs:
Describes the width and color of paths. The color can either be solid or provided by a callback. For more information, see [`ColorMode`]

The default stroke is the same as [`Stroke::NONE`].

2076.name: LayoutJob

968.name: visual_bounding_rect
968.docs: The visual bounding rectangle (includes stroke width)

741.name: texture_id
741.docs: The texture to use when drawing these triangles.

1922.name: baseline_offset_factor
1922.docs:
When using this font's metrics to layout a row,
shift the entire row downwards by this fraction of the font size (in points).

A positive value shifts the text downwards.
A negative value shifts it upwards.

2349.name: text
2349.docs: The full, non-elided text of the input job.

687.name: is_valid
687.docs: Are all indices within the bounds of the contained vertices?

133.name: same
133.docs: Same rounding on all four corners.

2222.name: expand_bg
2222.docs:
Amount to expand background fill by.

Default: 1.0

1668.name: tessellate_cubic_bezier
1668.docs:
Tessellate a single [`CubicBezierShape`] into a [`Mesh`].

* `cubic_shape`: the shape to tessellate.
* `out`: triangles are appended to this.

1768.name: cursor
1768.docs: Different types of text cursors, i.e. ways to point into a [`super::Galley`].

333.name: new
333.docs: Create an image filled with the given color.

1214.name: dashed_line_many_with_offset
1214.docs:
Turn a line into dashes with different dash/gap lengths and a start offset. If you need to
create many dashed lines use this instead of [`Self::dashed_line_with_offset`].

760.name: Mutex
760.docs:
Provides interior mutability.

This is a thin wrapper around [`parking_lot::Mutex`], except if
the feature `deadlock_detection` is turned enabled, in which case
extra checks are added to detect deadlocks.

2622.name: new
2622.docs: If you are using egui, use `egui::Context::load_texture` instead.

1187.name: Ellipse
1187.docs: Ellipse with optional outline and fill.

1287.name: with_angle
1287.docs:
Set text rotation to `angle` radians clockwise.
The pivot is `pos` (the upper left corner of the text).

2595.name: texture_options
2595.docs: The texture options suitable for a font texture

3022.name: clip_rect
3022.docs:
Clip / scissor rectangle.
Only show the part of the [`Mesh`] that falls within this.

2141.name: justify
2141.docs: Justify text so that word-wrapped rows fill the whole [`TextWrapping::max_width`].

2568.name: TAB_SIZE
2568.docs: One `\t` character is this many spaces wide.

1133.name: corner_radius
1133.docs:
How rounded the corners of the rectangle are.

Use [`CornerRadius::ZERO`] for for sharp corners.

This is the corner radii of the rectangle.
If there is a stroke, then the stroke will have an inner and outer corner radius,
and those will depend on [`StrokeKind`] and the stroke width.

For [`StrokeKind::Inside`], the outside of the stroke coincides with the rectangle,
so the rounding will in this case specify the outer corner radius.

1460.name: Middle
1460.docs: The stroke should be painted right on the edge of the shape, half inside and half outside.

2668.name: WHITE_UV
2668.docs:
The UV coordinate of a white region of the texture mesh.

The default egui texture has the top-left corner pixel fully white.
You need need use a clamping texture sampler for this to work
(so it doesn't do bilinear blending with bottom right corner).

1233.name: image
1233.docs:
An image at the given position.

`uv` should normally be `Rect::from_min_max(pos2(0.0, 0.0), pos2(1.0, 1.0))`
unless you want to crop or flip the image.

`tint` is a color multiplier. Use [`Color32::WHITE`] if you don't want to tint the image.

679.name: split_to_u16
679.docs:
This is for platforms that only support 16-bit index buffers.

Splits this mesh into many smaller meshes (if needed)
where the smaller meshes have 16-bit indices.

125.name: nw
125.docs: Radius of the rounding of the North-West (left top) corner.

1660.name: tessellate_ellipse
1660.docs:
Tessellate a single [`EllipseShape`] into a [`Mesh`].

* `shape`: the ellipse to tessellate.
* `out`: triangles are appended to this.

425.name: pos
425.docs:
If `None`, set the whole texture to [`Self::image`].

If `Some(pos)`, update a sub-region of an already allocated texture with the patch in [`Self::image`].

2060.name: new
2060.docs:
Create a new [`Fonts`] for text layout.
This call is expensive, so only create one [`Fonts`] and then reuse it.

* `pixels_per_point`: how many physical pixels per logical "point".
* `max_texture_side`: largest supported texture size (one side).

1833.name: families
1833.docs:
Which fonts (names) to use for each [`FontFamily`].

The list should be a list of keys into [`Self::font_data`].
When looking for a character glyph `epaint` will start with
the first font and then move to the second, and so on.
So the first font is the primary, and then comes a list of fallbacks in order of priority.

1279.name: fallback_color
1279.docs:
Any [`Color32::PLACEHOLDER`] in the galley will be replaced by the given color.
Affects everything: backgrounds, glyphs, strikethrough, underline, etc.

1606.name: debug_paint_clip_rects
1606.docs: Output the clip rectangles to be painted.

2133.name: sections
2133.docs: The different section, which can have different fonts, colors, etc.

2460.name: char_at
2460.docs:
Closest char at the desired x coordinate in row-relative coordinates.
Returns something in the range `[0, char_count_excluding_newline()]`.

344.name: region
344.docs:
Create a new image from a patch of the current image.

This method is especially convenient for screenshotting a part of the app
since `region` can be interpreted as screen coordinates of the entire screenshot if `pixels_per_point` is provided for the native application.
The floats of [`emath::Rect`] are cast to usize, rounding them down in order to interpret them as indices to the image data.

Panics if `region.min.x > region.max.x || region.min.y > region.max.y`, or if a region larger than the image is passed.

1879.name: font
1879.docs: The content of a `.ttf` or `.otf` file.

1652.name: Tessellator
1652.docs:
Converts [`Shape`]s into triangles ([`Mesh`]).

For performance reasons it is smart to reuse the same [`Tessellator`].

2533.name: uv_rect
2533.docs: Position and size of the glyph in the font texture, in texels.

1098.name: convex_polygon
1098.docs:
A convex polygon with a fill and optional stroke.

The most performant winding order is clockwise.

871.name: from_points_stroke
871.docs:
Creates a cubic Bézier curve based on 4 points and stroke.

The first point is the starting point and the last one is the ending point of the curve.
The middle points are the control points.

644.name: pos
644.docs:
Logical pixel coordinates (points).
(0,0) is the top left corner of the screen.

90.name: feathering_size_in_pixels
90.docs:
The size of the feathering, in physical pixels.

The default, and suggested, value for this is `1.0`.
If you use a larger value, edges will appear blurry.

2733.name: LINEAR_MIRRORED_REPEAT
2733.docs: Linear magnification and minification, but with the texture mirrored and repeated.

390.name: LIGHT_MODE_DEFAULT
390.docs: A good-looking default for light mode (black-on-white text).

2152.name: effective_wrap_width
2152.docs: The wrap with, with a small margin in some cases.

2806.name: MirroredRepeat
2806.docs: Mirrors the texture with each repetition, creating symmetrical tiling.

2579.name: PASSWORD_REPLACEMENT_CHAR
2579.docs: Suggested character to use to replace those in password text fields.

1144.name: with_round_to_pixels
1144.docs:
Snap the rectangle to pixels?

Rounding produces sharper rectangles.

If `None`, [`crate::TessellationOptions::round_rects_to_pixels`] will be used.

2352.name: concat
2352.docs: Append each galley under the previous one.

917.name: points
917.docs:
The first point is the starting point and the last one is the ending point of the curve.
The middle point is the control points.

136.name: at_most
136.docs: Make sure each corner has a rounding of at most this.

563.name: same
563.docs: The same margin on every side.

1771.name: min
1771.docs: Top left corner UV in texture.

2098.name: FontsImpl
2098.docs:
The collection of fonts used by `epaint`.

Required in order to paint text.

336.name: from_gray
336.docs:
Create a [`ColorImage`] from flat opaque gray data.

Panics if `size[0] * size[1] != gray.len()`.

2298.name: overflow_character
2298.docs:
Character to use to represent elided text.

The default is `…`.

If not set, no character will be used (but the text will still be elided).

2625.name: set_partial
2625.docs: Assign a new image to a subregion of the whole texture.

2071.name: row_height
2071.docs:
Height of one row of text in points.

Returns a value rounded to [`emath::GUI_ROUNDING`].

2725.name: TextureFilter
2725.docs: How the texture texels are filtered.

1290.name: transform
1290.docs: Move the shape by this many points, in-place.

1390.name: PaintStats
1390.docs: Collected allocation statistics for shapes and meshes.

2598.name: allocate
2598.docs:
Returns the coordinates of where the rect ended up,
and invalidates the region.

2698.name: options
2698.docs: The texture filtering mode to use when rendering.

2144.name: simple
2144.docs: Break on `\n` and at the given wrap width.

1136.name: round_rects_to_pixels
1136.docs:
If `true` (default), align rectangles to the physical pixel grid.

This makes the rectangle strokes more crisp,
and makes filled rectangles tile perfectly (without feathering).

You can override this with [`crate::RectShape::round_to_pixels`].

2344.name: num_vertices
2344.docs: Total number of vertices in all the row meshes.

1790.name: Font
1790.docs: Wrapper over multiple [`FontImpl`] (e.g. a primary + fallbacks for emojis)

2671.name: retain
2671.docs:
Increase the retain-count of the given texture.

For each time you call [`Self::retain`] you must call [`Self::free`] on additional time.

2998.name: clip_rect
2998.docs:
Clip / scissor rectangle.
Only show the part of the [`Shape`] that falls within this.

682.name: texture_id
682.docs: The texture to use when drawing these triangles.

128.name: se
128.docs: Radius of the rounding of the South-East (right bottom) corner.

2771.name: Nearest
2771.docs:
Show the nearest pixel value.

When zooming in you will get sharp, square pixels/texels.
When zooming out you will get a very crisp (and aliased) look.

228.name: at_least
228.docs: Make sure each corner has a rounding of at least this.

1990.name: families

1.name: fill_texture_id
1.docs:
If the rect should be filled with a texture, which one?

The texture is multiplied with [`crate::RectShape::fill`].

882.name: sample
882.docs:
Calculate the point (x,y) at t based on the cubic Bézier curve equation.
t is in [0.0,1.0]
[Bézier Curve](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%C3%A9zier_curve#Cubic_B.C3.A9zier_curves)

1209.name: closed_line
1209.docs: A line that closes back to the start point again.

428.name: TextureOptions
428.docs: How the texture texels are filtered.

1736.name: LayoutCursor
1736.docs:
Row/column cursor.

This refers to rows and columns in layout terms--text wrapping creates multiple rows.

2063.name: texture_atlas
2063.docs:
The font atlas.
Pass this to [`crate::Tessellator`].

1282.name: angle
1282.docs:
Rotate text by this many radians clockwise.
The pivot is `pos` (the upper left corner of the text).

1609.name: bezier_tolerance
1609.docs: The maximum distance between the original curve and the flattened curve.

2263.name: Extend
2263.docs: The text should expand the `Ui` size when reaching its boundary.

2036.name: Highest
2036.docs:
Prefer this font before all existing ones.

If a desired glyph exists in this font, it will be used.

928.name: for_each_flattened_with_t
928.docs:
Compute a flattened approximation of the curve, invoking a callback at
each step.

The callback takes the point and corresponding curve parameter at each step.

This implements the algorithm described by Raph Levien at
<https://raphlinus.github.io/graphics/curves/2019/12/23/flatten-quadbez.html>

2136.name: first_row_min_height
2136.docs:
The first row must be at least this high.
This is in case we lay out text that is the continuation
of some earlier text (sharing the same row),
in which case this will be the height of the earlier text.
In other cases, set this to `0.0`.

701.name: transform
701.docs: Transform the mesh in-place with the given transform.

1228.name: galley
1228.docs:
Any uncolored parts of the [`Galley`] (using [`Color32::PLACEHOLDER`]) will be replaced with the given color.

Any non-placeholder color in the galley takes precedence over this fallback color.

1882.name: tweak
1882.docs: Extra scale and vertical tweak to apply to all text of this font.

1655.name: PreparedDisc
1655.docs: A pre-rasterized disc (filled circle), somewhere in the texture atlas.

874.name: PathShape
874.docs: A path which can be stroked and/or filled (if closed).

647.name: Vertex
647.docs:
The 2D vertex type.

Should be friendly to send to GPU as is.

1955.name: default
1955.docs:
Specifies the default fonts if the feature `default_fonts` is enabled,
otherwise this is the same as [`Self::empty`].

1501.name: inside
1501.docs: Set the stroke to be painted entirely inside of the shape

1601.name: feathering
1601.docs:
Use "feathering" to smooth out the edges of shapes as a form of anti-aliasing.

Feathering works by making each edge into a thin gradient into transparency.
The size of this edge is controlled by [`Self::feathering_size_in_pixels`].

This makes shapes appear smoother, but requires more triangles and is therefore slower.

This setting does not affect text.

Default: `true`.

2582.name: r
2582.docs: The radius of this disc in texels.

820.name: offset
820.docs:
Move the shadow by this much.

For instance, a value of `[1.0, 2.0]` will move the shadow 1 point to the right and 2 points down,
causing a drop-shadow effect.

1147.name: visual_bounding_rect
1147.docs: The visual bounding rectangle (includes stroke width)

2355.name: cursor_from_pos
2355.docs:
Cursor at the given position within the galley.

A cursor above the galley is considered
same as a cursor at the start,
and a cursor below the galley is considered
same as a cursor at the end.
This allows implementing text-selection by dragging above/below the galley.

2128.name: layout
2128.docs:
Layout text into a [`Galley`].

In most cases you should use [`crate::Fonts::layout_job`] instead
since that memoizes the input, making subsequent layouting of the same text much faster.

693.name: colored_vertex
693.docs:
Add a colored vertex.

Panics when the mesh has assigned a texture.

2455.name: RowVisuals
2455.docs: The tessellated output of a row.

466.name: Margin
466.docs:
A value for all four sides of a rectangle,
often used to express padding or spacing.

Can be added and subtracted to/from [`Rect`]s.

Negative margins are possible, but may produce weird behavior.
Use with care.

All values are stored as [`i8`] to keep the size of [`Margin`] small.
If you want floats, use [`crate::MarginF32`] instead.

2882.name: from_bottom_px
2882.docs:
Physical pixel offset for bottom side of the viewport.

This is what `glViewport`, `glScissor` etc expects for the y axis.

339.name: from_rgb
339.docs:
Create a [`ColorImage`] from flat RGB data.

This is what you want to use after having loaded an image file (and if
you are ignoring the alpha channel - considering it to always be 0xff)

Panics if `size[0] * size[1] * 3 != rgb.len()`.

2528.name: font_height
2528.docs: The row/line height of this font.

1093.name: fill
1093.docs: Fill is only supported for convex polygons.

2301.name: from_wrap_mode_and_width
2301.docs: Create a [`TextWrapping`] from a [`TextWrapMode`] and an available width.

2074.name: layout_no_wrap
2074.docs:
Will line break at `\n`.

The implementation uses memoization so repeated calls are cheap.

2728.name: TextureWrapMode
2728.docs: Defines how textures are wrapped around objects when texture coordinates fall outside the [0, 1] range.

85.name: Solid
85.docs: The entire path is one solid color, this is the default.

739.name: indices
739.docs:
Draw as triangles (i.e. the length is always multiple of three).

egui is NOT consistent with what winding order it uses, so turn off backface culling.

1066.name: callback
1066.docs:
Paint something custom (e.g. 3D stuff).

The concrete value of `callback` depends on the rendering backend used. For instance, the
`glow` backend requires that callback be an `egui_glow::CallbackFn` while the `wgpu`
backend requires a `egui_wgpu::Callback`.

If the type cannot be downcast to the type expected by the current backend the callback
will not be drawn.

The rendering backend is responsible for first setting the active viewport to
[`Self::rect`].

The rendering backend is also responsible for restoring any state, such as the bound shader
program, vertex array, etc.

Shape has to be clone, therefore this has to be an `Arc` instead of a `Box`.

2147.name: simple_singleline
2147.docs: Does not break on `\n`, but shows the replacement character instead.

1920.name: y_offset_factor
1920.docs:
Shift font's glyphs downwards by this fraction of the font size (in points).
this is only a visual effect and does not affect the text layout.

Affects larger font sizes more.

A positive value shifts the text downwards.
A negative value shifts it upwards.

Example value: `-0.2`.

1139.name: brush
1139.docs:
Controls texturing, if any.

Since most rectangles do not have a texture, this is optional and in an `Arc`,
so that [`RectShape`] is kept small..

1239.name: translate
1239.docs:
Move the shape by `delta`, in-place.

A wrapper around [`Self::transform`].

685.name: clear
685.docs: Restore to default state, but without freeing memory.

131.name: CornerRadius
131.docs:
How rounded the corners of things should be.

This specific the _corner radius_ of the underlying geometric shape (e.g. rectangle).
If there is a stroke, then the stroke will have an inner and outer corner radius
which will depends on its width and [`crate::StrokeKind`].

The rounding uses `u8` to save space,
so the amount of rounding is limited to integers in the range `[0, 255]`.

For calculations, you may want to use [`crate::CornerRadiusF32`] instead, which uses `f32`.

1666.name: tessellate_text
1666.docs:
Tessellate a single [`TextShape`] into a [`Mesh`].
* `text_shape`: the text to tessellate.
* `out`: triangles are appended to this.

4.name: uv
4.docs:
What UV coordinates to use for the texture?

To display a texture, set [`Self::fill_texture_id`],
and set this to `Rect::from_min_max(pos2(0.0, 0.0), pos2(1.0, 1.0))`.

Use [`Rect::ZERO`] to turn off texturing.

885.name: for_each_flattened_with_t
885.docs: Iterates through the curve invoking a callback at each point.

1212.name: dashed_line_with_offset
1212.docs: Turn a line into dashes with different dash/gap lengths and a start offset.

331.name: pixels
331.docs: The pixels, row by row, from top to bottom.

431.name: partial
431.docs: Update a sub-region of an existing texture.

2620.name: TextureHandle
2620.docs:
Used to paint images.

An _image_ is pixels stored in RAM, and represented using [`ImageData`].
Before you can paint it however, you need to convert it to a _texture_.

If you are using egui, use `egui::Context::load_texture`.

The [`TextureHandle`] can be cloned cheaply.
When the last [`TextureHandle`] for specific texture is dropped, the texture is freed.

See also [`TextureManager`].

2066.name: font_image_size
2066.docs:
Current size of the font image.
Pass this to [`crate::Tessellator`].

1185.name: Circle
1185.docs: Circle with optional outline and fill.

1612.name: validate_meshes
1612.docs:
If `true`, invalid meshes will be silently ignored.
If `false`, invalid meshes will cause a panic.

The default is `false` to save performance.

2493.name: glyph_index_start
2493.docs:
The number of triangle indices added before the first glyph triangle.

This can be used to insert more triangles after the background but before the glyphs,
i.e. for text selection visualization.

2266.name: TextWrapMode
2266.docs:
How to wrap and elide text.

This enum is used in high-level APIs where providing a [`TextWrapping`] is too verbose.

2666.name: Managed
2666.docs:
Textures allocated using [`TextureManager`].

The first texture (`TextureId::Managed(0)`) is used for the font data.

2112.name: has_glyphs
2112.docs: Can we display all the glyphs in this text?

1658.name: tessellate_shape
1658.docs:
Tessellate a single [`Shape`] into a [`Mesh`].

This call can panic the given shape is of [`Shape::Vec`] or [`Shape::Callback`].
For that, use [`Self::tessellate_clipped_shape`] instead.
* `shape`: the shape to tessellate.
* `out`: triangles are appended to this.

223.name: sw
223.docs: Radius of the rounding of the South-West (left bottom) corner.

2185.name: leading_space
2185.docs: Can be used for first row indentation.

1958.name: builtin_font_names
1958.docs: List of all the builtin font names used by `epaint`.

2058.name: begin_pass
2058.docs:
Call at the start of each frame with the latest known
`pixels_per_point`, `max_texture_side`, and `text_alpha_from_coverage`.

Call after painting the previous frame, but before using [`Fonts`] for the new frame.

This function will react to changes in `pixels_per_point`, `max_texture_side`, and `text_alpha_from_coverage`,
as well as notice when the font atlas is getting full, and handle that.

1831.name: Monospace
1831.docs:
A font where each character is the same width (`w` is the same width as `i`).

Useful for code snippets, or when you need to align numbers or text.

1277.name: layout_job
1277.docs:
Layout some text.

This is the most advanced layout function.
See also [`Self::layout`], [`Self::layout_no_wrap`] and
[`Self::layout_delayed_color`].

The implementation uses memoization so repeated calls are cheap.

1604.name: round_text_to_pixels
1604.docs:
If `true` (default) align text to the physical pixel grid.
This makes the text sharper on most platforms.

1050.name: ViewportInPixels
1050.docs: Size of the viewport in whole, physical pixels.

823.name: color
823.docs: Color of the opaque center of the shadow.

923.name: to_path_shape
923.docs:
Convert the quadratic Bézier curve to one [`PathShape`].
The `tolerance` will be used to control the max distance between the curve and the base line.

696.name: reserve_vertices
696.docs:
Make room for this many additional vertices.
See also `reserve_triangles`.

2458.name: char_count_excluding_newline
2458.docs: Excludes the implicit `\n` after the [`Row`], if any.

469.name: same
469.docs: The same margin on every side.

1223.name: Fonts
1223.docs:
The collection of fonts used by `epaint`.

Required in order to paint text. Create one and reuse. Cheap to clone.

Each [`Fonts`] comes with a font atlas textures that needs to be used when painting.

If you are using `egui`, use `egui::Context::set_fonts` and `egui::Context::fonts`.

You need to call [`Self::begin_pass`] and [`Self::font_image_delta`] once every frame.

1550.name: stroke_closed
1550.docs: A closed path (returning to the first point).

2531.name: font_impl_ascent
2531.docs: The ascent of the sub-font within the font (`FontImpl`).

1096.name: line
1096.docs:
A line through many points.

Use [`Shape::line_segment`] instead if your line only connects two points.

1423.name: round_center_to_pixel
1423.docs:
For vertical or horizontal lines:
round the stroke center to produce a sharp, pixel-aligned line.

2304.name: truncate_at_width
2304.docs: Elide text that doesn't fit within the given width, replaced with `…`.

1196.name: TextShape
1196.docs:
How to paint some text on screen.

This needs to be recreated if `pixels_per_point` (dpi scale) changes.

742.name: is_valid
742.docs: Are all indices within the bounds of the contained vertices?

1723.docs:
Two `CCursor`s are considered equal if they refer to the same character boundary,
even if one prefers the start of the next row.

388.name: TwoCoverageMinusCoverageSq
388.docs:
`alpha = 2 * coverage - coverage^2`

This looks good for white-on-black text, i.e. dark mode.

Very similar to a gamma of 0.5, but produces sharper text.
See <https://www.desmos.com/calculator/w0ndf5blmn> for a comparison to gamma=0.5.

2150.name: append
2150.docs: Helper for adding a new section when building a [`LayoutJob`].

1042.name: rect
1042.docs:
Where to paint.

This will become [`PaintCallbackInfo::viewport`].

2804.name: ClampToEdge
2804.docs:
Stretches the edge pixels to fill beyond the texture's bounds.

This is what you want to use for a normal image in a GUI.

134.name: is_same
134.docs: Do all corners have the same rounding?

2877.name: hash
2877.docs: Hash the given value with a predictable hasher.

1769.name: offset
1769.docs: X/Y offset for nice rendering (unit: points).

1215.name: convex_polygon
1215.docs:
A convex polygon with a fill and optional stroke.

The most performant winding order is clockwise.

334.name: filled
334.docs: Create an image filled with the given color.

2296.name: max_rows
2296.docs:
Maximum amount of rows the text galley should have.

If this limit is reached, text will be truncated
and [`Self::overflow_character`] appended to the final row.
You can detect this by checking [`Galley::elided`].

If set to `0`, no text will be outputted.

If set to `1`, a single row will be outputted,
eliding the text after [`Self::max_width`] is reached.
When you set `max_rows = 1`, it is recommended you also set [`Self::break_anywhere`] to `true`.

Default value: `usize::MAX`.

2069.name: has_glyphs
2069.docs: Can we display all the glyphs in this text?

1288.name: with_angle_and_anchor
1288.docs:
Set the text rotation to the `angle` radians clockwise.
The pivot is determined by the given `anchor` point on the text bounding box.

3023.name: primitive
3023.docs: What to paint - either a [`Mesh`] or a [`PaintCallback`].

1134.name: stroke_kind
1134.docs:
Is the stroke on the inside, outside, or centered on the rectangle?

If you want to perfectly tile rectangles, use [`StrokeKind::Inside`].

1461.name: Outside
1461.docs: The stroke should be painted entirely outside of the shape

1234.name: visual_bounding_rect
1234.docs: The visual bounding rectangle (includes stroke widths)

680.name: indices
680.docs:
Draw as triangles (i.e. the length is always multiple of three).

If you only support 16-bit indices you can use [`Mesh::split_to_u16`].

egui is NOT consistent with what winding order it uses, so turn off backface culling.

2769.name: default
2769.docs: The default is linear for both magnification and minification.

126.name: ne
126.docs: Radius of the rounding of the North-East (right top) corner.

1661.name: tessellate_mesh
1661.docs:
Tessellate a single [`Mesh`] into a [`Mesh`].

* `mesh`: the mesh to tessellate.
* `out`: triangles are appended to this.

226.name: same
226.docs: Same rounding on all four corners.

3069.name: epaint
3069.docs:
A simple 2D graphics library for turning simple 2D shapes and text into textured triangles.

Made for [`egui`](https://github.com/emilk/egui/).

Create some [`Shape`]:s and pass them to [`Tessellator::tessellate_shapes`] to generate [`Mesh`]:es
that you can then paint using some graphics API of your choice (e.g. OpenGL).

## Coordinate system
The left-top corner of the screen is `(0.0, 0.0)`,
with X increasing to the right and Y increasing downwards.

`epaint` uses logical _points_ as its coordinate system.
Those related to physical _pixels_ by the `pixels_per_point` scale factor.
For example, a high-dpi screen can have `pixels_per_point = 2.0`,
meaning there are two physical screen pixels for each logical point.

Angles are in radians, and are measured clockwise from the X-axis, which has angle=0.

## Feature flags

426.name: image
426.docs:
What to set the texture to.

If [`Self::pos`] is `None`, this describes the whole texture.

If [`Self::pos`] is `Some`, this describes a patch of the whole image starting at [`Self::pos`].

1734.name: row
1734.docs:
0 is first row, and so on.
Note that a single paragraph can span multiple rows.
(a paragraph is text separated by `\n`).

1834.name: Name

1280.name: override_text_color
1280.docs:
If set, the text color in the galley will be ignored and replaced
with the given color.

This only affects the glyphs and will NOT replace background color nor strikethrough/underline color.

826.name: as_shape
826.docs: The argument is the rectangle of the shadow caster.

926.name: sample
926.docs:
Calculate the point (x,y) at t based on the quadratic Bézier curve equation.
t is in [0.0,1.0]
[Bézier Curve](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%C3%A9zier_curve#Quadratic_B.C3.A9zier_curves)

2134.name: wrap
2134.docs: Controls the text wrapping and elision.

699.name: Mesh16
699.docs:
A version of [`Mesh`] that uses 16-bit indices.

This is produced by [`Mesh::split_to_u16`] and is meant to be used for legacy render backends.

2107.name: new
2107.docs:
Create a new [`FontsImpl`] for text layout.
This call is expensive, so only create one [`FontsImpl`] and then reuse it.

1226.name: FontId
1226.docs: How to select a sized font.

1553.name: fill
1553.docs:
The path is taken to be closed (i.e. returning to the start again).

Calling this may reverse the vertices in the path if they are wrong winding order.
The preferred winding order is clockwise.

1653.name: prepared_discs
1653.docs: Returns the locations and sizes of pre-rasterized discs (filled circles) in this atlas.

1099.name: visual_bounding_rect
1099.docs: The visual bounding rectangle (includes stroke width)

872.name: transform
872.docs: Transform the curve with the given transform.

1199.name: Mesh
1199.docs:
A general triangle mesh.

Can be used to display images.

Wrapped in an [`Arc`] to minimize the size of [`Shape`].

2961.name: User
2961.docs:
Your own texture, defined in any which way you want.
The backend renderer will presumably use this to look up what texture to use.

645.name: uv
645.docs:
Normalized texture coordinates.
(0, 0) is the top left corner of the texture.
(1, 1) is the bottom right corner of the texture.

2734.name: NEAREST_REPEAT
2734.docs: Nearest magnification and minification, but with the texture repeated.

91.name: UV
91.docs:
Provide a callback which takes in the path's bounding box and a position and converts it to a color.
When used with a path, the bounding box will have a margin of [`TessellationOptions::feathering_size_in_pixels`](`crate::tessellator::TessellationOptions::feathering_size_in_pixels`)

**This cannot be serialized**

1953.name: font_data
1953.docs:
List of font names and their definitions.

`epaint` has built-in-default for these, but you can override them if you like.

291.name: from_rgba_unmultiplied

1499.name: middle
1499.docs: Set the stroke to be painted right on the edge of the shape, half inside and half outside.

391.name: DARK_MODE_DEFAULT
391.docs: A good-looking default for dark mode (white-on-black text).

1045.name: screen_size_px
1045.docs: Full size of the screen, in pixels.

1145.name: with_blur_width
1145.docs:
If larger than zero, the edges of the rectangle
(for both fill and stroke) will be blurred.

This can be used to produce shadows and glow effects.

The blur is currently implemented using a simple linear blur in `sRGBA` gamma space.

2453.name: size
2453.docs:
Logical size based on font heights etc.
Includes leading and trailing whitespace.

691.name: append
691.docs:
Append all the indices and vertices of `other` to `self`.

Panics when `other` mesh has a different texture.

2880.name: left_px
2880.docs: Physical pixel offset for left side of the viewport.

564.name: symmetric
564.docs: Margins with the same size on opposing sides

337.name: from_gray_iter
337.docs:
Alternative method to `from_gray`.
Create a [`ColorImage`] from iterator over flat opaque gray data.

Panics if `size[0] * size[1] != gray_iter.len()`.

2526.name: pos
2526.docs:
Baseline position, relative to the row.
Logical position: pos.y is the same for all chars of the same [`TextFormat`].

1091.name: points
1091.docs: Filled paths should prefer clockwise order.

2299.name: elided
2299.docs: Set to true the text was truncated due to [`TextWrapping::max_rows`].

864.name: points
864.docs:
The first point is the starting point and the last one is the ending point of the curve.
The middle points are the control points.

2072.name: families
2072.docs: List of all known font families.

2726.name: minification
2726.docs: How to filter when minifying (when texels are smaller than pixels).

964.name: Stroke
964.docs:
Describes the width and color of a line.

The default stroke is the same as [`Stroke::NONE`].

2699.name: bytes_used
2699.docs:
Size in bytes.
width x height x [`Self::bytes_per_pixel`].

1691.name: prefer_next_row
1691.docs:
If this cursors sits right at the border of a wrapped row break (NOT paragraph break)
do we prefer the next row?
This is *almost* always what you want, *except* for when
explicitly clicking the end of a row or pressing the end key.

1137.name: round_to_pixels
1137.docs:
Snap the rectangle to pixels?

Rounding produces sharper rectangles.

If `None`, [`crate::TessellationOptions::round_rects_to_pixels`] will be used.

2345.name: num_indices
2345.docs: Total number of indices in all the row meshes.

2672.name: TexturesDelta
2672.docs:
What has been allocated and freed during the last period.

These are commands given to the integration painter.
attrs: #[must_use = "The painter must take care of this"]

1237.name: transform
1237.docs:
Move the shape by this many points, in-place.

If using a [`PaintCallback`], note that only the rect is scaled as opposed
to other shapes where the stroke is also scaled.

2772.name: Linear
2772.docs: Linearly interpolate the nearest neighbors, creating a smoother look when zooming in and out.

129.name: StrokeKind
129.docs: Describes how the stroke of a shape should be painted.

2218.name: extra_letter_spacing
2218.docs:
Extra spacing between letters, in points.

Default: 0.0.

For even text it is recommended you round this to an even number of _pixels_.

1664.name: tessellate_path
1664.docs:
Tessellate a single [`PathShape`] into a [`Mesh`].

* `path_shape`: the path to tessellate.
* `out`: triangles are appended to this.

229.name: at_most
229.docs: Make sure each corner has a rounding of at most this.

883.name: flatten
883.docs:
find a set of points that approximate the cubic Bézier curve.
the number of points is determined by the tolerance.
the points may not be evenly distributed in the range [0.0,1.0] (t value)

2.name: TextureId
2.docs:
What texture to use in a [`Mesh`] mesh.

If you don't want to use a texture, use `TextureId::Managed(0)` and the [`WHITE_UV`] for uv-coord.

329.name: source_size
329.docs: Size of the original SVG image (if any), or just the texel size of the image.

1210.name: dotted_line
1210.docs: Turn a line into equally spaced dots.

1537.name: add_circle_quadrant
1537.docs:
Add one quadrant of a circle

* quadrant 0: right bottom
* quadrant 1: left bottom
* quadrant 2: left top
* quadrant 3: right top

429.name: ImageDelta
429.docs:
A change to an image.

Either a whole new image, or an update to a rectangular region of it.
attrs: #[must_use = "The painter must take care of this"]

1183.name: Vec
1183.docs:
Recursively nest more shapes - sometimes a convenience to be able to do.
For performance reasons it is better to avoid it.

2064.name: TextureAtlas
2064.docs:
Contains font data in an atlas, where each character occupied a small rectangle.

More characters can be added, possibly expanding the texture.

1283.name: new
1283.docs:
The given fallback color will be used for any uncolored part of the galley (using [`Color32::PLACEHOLDER`]).

Any non-placeholder color in the galley takes precedence over this fallback color.

2491.name: mesh
2491.docs:
The tessellated text, using non-normalized (texel) UV coordinates.
That is, you need to divide the uv coordinates by the texture size.

Use this font as a fallback, after all existing ones.

This font will only be used if the glyph is not found in any of the previously installed fonts.

2137.name: break_on_newline
2137.docs:
If `true`, all `\n` characters will result in a new _paragraph_,
starting on a new row.

If `false`, all `\n` characters will be ignored
and show up as the replacement character.

Default: `true`.

2337.name: job

The job that this galley is the result of.
Contains the original string and style sections.

2537.name: logical_rect
2537.docs: Same y range for all characters with the same [`TextFormat`].

221.name: nw
221.docs: Radius of the rounding of the North-West (left top) corner.

875.name: to_path_shapes
875.docs:
Convert the cubic Bézier curve to one or two [`PathShape`]'s.
When the curve is closed and it has to intersect with the base line, it will be converted into two shapes.
Otherwise, it will be converted into one shape.
The `tolerance` will be used to control the max distance between the curve and the base line.
The `epsilon` is used when comparing two floats.

1502.name: is_empty

1602.name: coarse_tessellation_culling

If `true` (default) cull certain primitives before tessellating them.
This likely makes

821.name: blur
821.docs:
The width of the blur, i.e. the width of the fuzzy penumbra.

A value of 0 means a sharp shadow.

921.name: from_points_stroke
921.docs:
Create a new quadratic Bézier shape based on the 3 points and stroke.

The first point is the starting point and the last one is the ending point of the curve.
The middle point is the control points.
The points should be in the order [start, control, end]

2456.name: ends_with_newline
2456.docs:
If true, this [`Row`] came from a paragraph ending with a `\n`.
The `\n` itself is omitted from [`Self::glyphs`].
A `\n` in the input text always creates a new [`Row`] below it,
so that text that ends with `\n` has an empty [`Row`] last.
This also implies that the last [`Row`] in a [`Galley`] always has `ends_with_newline == false`.

467.name: MarginF32
467.docs:
A value for all four sides of a rectangle,
often used to express padding or spacing.

Can be added and subtracted to/from [`Rect`]s.

For storage, use [`crate::Margin`] instead.

2229.name: valign
2229.docs:
If you use a small font and [`Align::TOP`] you
can get the effect of raised text.

If you use a small font and [`Align::BOTTOM`]
you get the effect of a subscript.

If you use [`Align::Center`], you get text that is centered
around a common center-line, which is nice when mixining emojis
and normal text in e.g. a button.

794.name: RwLock
794.docs:
Provides interior mutability.

This is a thin wrapper around [`parking_lot::RwLock`], except if
the feature `deadlock_detection` is turned enabled, in which case
extra checks are added to detect deadlocks.

340.name: example
340.docs: An example color image, useful for tests.

1548.name: fill_and_stroke
1548.docs:
The path is taken to be closed (i.e. returning to the start again).

Calling this may reverse the vertices in the path if they are wrong winding order.
The preferred winding order is clockwise.

2529.name: line_height
2529.docs:
Height of this row of text.

Usually same as [`Self::font_height`],
unless explicitly overridden by [`TextFormat::line_height`].

1094.name: stroke
1094.docs: Color and thickness of the line.

2302.name: no_max_width
2302.docs: A row can be as long as it need to be.

1194.name: Rect
1194.docs: Rectangle with optional outline and fill.

2075.name: layout_delayed_color
2075.docs:
Like [`Self::layout`], made for when you want to pick a color for the text later.

The implementation uses memoization so repeated calls are cheap.

2729.name: mipmap_mode
2729.docs:
How to filter between texture mipmaps.

Mipmaps ensures textures look smooth even when the texture is very small and pixels are much
larger than individual texels.

# Notes

- This may not be available on all backends (currently only `egui_glow`).

1394.name: ClippedPrimitive
1394.docs:
A [`Mesh`] or [`PaintCallback`] within a clip rectangle.

Everything is using logical points.

386.name: Linear
386.docs:
`alpha = coverage`.

Looks good for black-on-white text, i.e. light mode.

Same as [`Self::Gamma`]`(1.0)`, but more efficient.

1921.name: y_offset
1921.docs:
Shift font's glyphs downwards by this amount of logical points.
this is only a visual effect and does not affect the text layout.

Affects all font sizes equally.

Example value: `2.0`.

32.name: into
32.docs: Calls `U::from(self)`. That is, this conversion is whatever the implementation of [From]<T> for U chooses to do.

1794.name: FontFamily
1794.docs:
Font of unknown size.

Which style of font: [`Monospace`][`FontFamily::Monospace`], [`Proportional`][`FontFamily::Proportional`],
or by user-chosen name.

2675.name: allocated
2675.docs: Get meta-data about all allocated textures in some arbitrary order.

686.name: bytes_used

* `quadratic_shape`: the shape to tessellate.
* `out`: triangles are appended to this.

1213.name: dashed_line_many
1213.docs:
Turn a line into dashes. If you need to create many dashed lines use this instead of
[`Self::dashed_line`].

1540.name: Path
1540.docs:
A connected line (without thickness or gaps) which can be tessellated
to either to a stroke (with thickness) or a filled convex area.
Used as a scratch-pad during tessellation.

432.name: is_whole
432.docs:
Is this affecting the whole texture?
If `false`, this is a partial (sub-region) update.

2621.name: TextureManager
2621.docs:
Low-level manager for allocating textures.

Communicates with the painting subsystem using [`Self::take_delta`].

2067.name: glyph_width
2067.docs: Width of this character in points.

1286.name: with_override_text_color
1286.docs: Use the given color for the text, regardless of what color is already in the galley.

2494.name: glyph_vertex_range
2494.docs:
The range of vertices in the mesh that contain glyphs (as opposed to background, underlines, strikethorugh, etc).

The glyph vertices comes after backgrounds (if any), but before any underlines and strikethrough.

2594.name: fill_ratio
2594.docs: When this get high, it might be time to clear and start over!

2694.name: name
2694.docs: A human-readable name useful for debugging.

2140.name: max_width
2140.docs:
Wrap text so that no row is wider than this.

If you would rather truncate text that doesn't fit, set [`Self::max_rows`] to `1`.

Set `max_width` to [`f32::INFINITY`] to turn off wrapping and elision.

Note that `\n` always produces a new row
if [`LayoutJob::break_on_newline`] is `true`.

478.name: is_same
478.docs: Are the margin on every side the same?

1132.name: Inside
1132.docs: The stroke should be painted entirely inside of the shape

2667.name: alloc
2667.docs:
Allocate a new texture.

The given name can be useful for later debugging.

The returned [`TextureId`] will be [`TextureId::Managed`], with an index
starting from zero and increasing with each call to [`Self::alloc`].

The first texture you allocate will be `TextureId::Managed(0) == TextureId::default()` and
MUST have a white pixel at (0,0) ([`crate::WHITE_UV`]).

The texture is given a retain-count of `1`, requiring one call to [`Self::free`] to free it.

1659.name: tessellate_circle
1659.docs:
Tessellate a single [`CircleShape`] into a [`Mesh`].

* `shape`: the circle to tessellate.
* `out`: triangles are appended to this.

224.name: se
224.docs: Radius of the rounding of the South-East (right bottom) corner.

878.name: split_range
878.docs: split the original cubic curve into a new one within a range.

1205.name: line
1205.docs:
A line through many points.

Use [`Self::line_segment`] instead if your line only connects two points.

2413.name: rect
2413.docs:
Logical bounding rectangle on font heights etc.

This ignores / includes the `LayoutSection::leading_space`.

3067.name: HAS_RAYON
3067.docs: Was epaint compiled with the `rayon` feature?

2840.name: set
2840.docs: New or changed textures. Apply before painting.

2059.name: font_image_delta
2059.docs: Call at the end of each frame (before painting) to get the change to the font texture since last call.

1278.name: underline
1278.docs:
Add this underline to the whole text.
You can also set an underline when creating the galley.

1605.name: round_line_segments_to_pixels
1605.docs:
If `true` (default), align right-angled line segments to the physical pixel grid.

This makes the line segments appear crisp on any display.

1051.name: clip_rect_in_pixels

The color and fuzziness of a fuzzy shape.

Can be used for a rectangular shadow with a soft penumbra.

Very similar to a box-shadow in CSS.

924.name: visual_bounding_rect

1097.name: closed_line

Text.

2078.name: font_atlas_fill_ratio

This increases as new fonts and/or glyphs are used,

The height of the tallest font used in the job.

389.name: AlphaFromCoverage

2805.name: Repeat

1043.name: viewport
1043.docs:
Viewport in points.

This specifies where on the screen to paint, and the borders of this
Rect is the [-1, +1] of the Normalized Device Coordinates.

Note than only a portion of this may be visible due to [`Self::clip_rect`].

This comes from [`PaintCallback::rect`].

2351.name: intrinsic_size

This is the size that a non-wrapped, non-truncated, non-justified version of the text
would have.

Useful for advanced layouting.

689.name: triangles

135.name: at_least

1670.name: tessellate_shapes
1670.docs:
Turns [`Shape`]:s into sets of triangles.

The given shapes will tessellated in the same order as they are given.
They will be batched together by clip rectangle.

* `pixels_per_point`: number of physical pixels to each logical point
* `options`: tessellation quality
* `shapes`: what to tessellate
* `font_tex_size`: size of the font texture. Required to normalize glyph uv rectangles when tessellating text.
* `prepared_discs`: What [`crate::TextureAtlas::prepared_discs`] returns. Can safely be set to an empty vec.

The implementation uses a [`Tessellator`].

## Returns
A list of clip rectangles with matching [`Mesh`].
